headline.main: SANDWICH ISLANDS.; Burning of the Whaleship Warren.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Polynesian gives the following account of the burning of the whaleship Warren: The ship Warren, of Holmes' Hole, Capt. R. N. SMITH, returned to this port on the 7th Jan. to re pair damages sustained by fire at sea since leaving this port in November last.

docs.lead_paragraph: DEATHS.--From the Health Officer's Report for the week ending March 12, we learn that there were but 48 deaths; 30 of this number were males, and 18 females; 18 of these were adults, and 30 children.

headline.main: ENGLAND.; The Maynooth Grant-Opposition Tactics--Lord John Russell--New Crystal Palace--The Nonconformists--Railway Termini--Australian Passages--Effect of the Milan Insurrection--Miscellaneous.

docs.lead_paragraph: The parliamentary piece de resistance on Monday and Wednesday evenings in St. Stephen's, was the Maynooth grant. This bone of contention between rival religions and parties, is regularly flung down once a year on the floor of the House, and in variably the subject of fierce debate for several evenings.

byline.original: Correspondence of the New-York Daily Times

docs.lead_paragraph: The late shocking murders of Mrs. Shaw and Mrs. Lynch, at Philadelphia, of which we have given accounts, are creating much excitement in that vicinity. The Philadelphia papers are full of the details. According to the Bulletin: "On the body of Mrs. Lynch was found a gold ring on the pubis, and a leather sheath of a dirk knife under her left arm. The wounds were in all forty-six.
